## the three election years needed
electDF <- electDF %>% 
  select(-c(office, version)) %>% 
  filter(year %in% c(2008, 2012, 2016)) %>% 
  mutate_at(vars(year, candidatevotes, totalvotes), as.integer) %>%
  mutate_at(vars(FIPS), as.character) %>% 
  mutate_at(vars(FIPS), str_pad, width = 5, pad = '0', side = 'left')

  select(c(FIPStxt, Stabr, area_name, Unemployment_rate_2008, Unemployment_rate_2012,
           Unemployment_rate_2016)) %>% 
  rename(FIPS = FIPStxt, State = Stabr, Region = area_name)

  ## modify, filter, and select the data to plot
  p <- electGeo %>% 
    filter(year == years[i], party == 'democrat') %>% 
    select(FIPS, votePercent, geometry) %>% 
    ## generate the base plot
    ggplot() +
    geom_sf(aes(geometry=geometry, fill = votePercent), color = 'grey60') +
    ## customize the fill (low is Republic 'Red', high corresponds to 'Democrat Blue')
    scale_fill_gradient2(low = '#E9141D', mid = 'grey80', high = '#0015BC',
                         midpoint = .5, name = 'Percent of Total Votes\nfor Democrat',
                         labels = scales::percent) +
    ## add the lake data to clean-up plot around the great lakes
    geom_sf(data = lakeMap, aes(geometry = geometry), fill = 'white', color = NA) +
    ## add state boundaries
    geom_sf(data = usMap, aes(geometry = geometry), fill = NA, color = 'grey10') +
    ## trim the coordinates of the map to zoom on CONUS
    coord_sf(xlim = c(-127, -66), ylim = c(22.5, 50) , expand = FALSE) +
    ## relabel the axes to include degree symbol
    scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::label_number(suffix = "°")) +
    scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::label_number(suffix = "°")) +
    ## modify the theme to my taste
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(panel.grid = element_blank(), axis.line  = element_line(color = "grey10")) +
    ## update the axis labels
    xlab('Longitude') +
    ylab('Latitude') +
    ## add the titles
    labs(title = titles[i],
         subtitle = subtitles[i])
  
  ## print the map to the screen
  print(p)
}

The series of choropleths above show the growing polarization in the United States national politic. In 2008, the county-aggregated election results indicate that many counties (43 percent) were closely divided as to their prefered candidate (that is where the percent of votes cast for either candidate was between 40 and 60 percent of county total). By 2012 that number dropped to 34 percent and in the 2016 Presidential Election that number was just 19 percent. This stark divide is particularly distinct amongst rural and suburban counties, which began to vote overwhelming Republican, while more urban counties voted distinctly Democratic.

Create Data Import Functions

def importXLS(filename, sheet_name, skiprows = 0, header = 0):
    '''
    Imports the XLS-formatted data and checks the import quality
    Inputs: filename (str), sheet_name (str or int), skiprows(int), header(int)
    Outputs: DF (Pandas DF)
    '''
    
    #import the dataset
    DF = pd.read_excel(filename, sheet_name = sheet_name,
                        skiprows = skiprows, header = header)
    
    #check the quality of the import
    print(DF.head())
    
    return DF
def importData(filename):
    '''
    Imports the data and checks the import quality
    Inputs: filename (str)
    Outputs: DF (Pandas DF)
    '''
    
    #import the dataset
    DF = pd.read_csv(filename)
    
    #check the quality of the import
    print(DF.head())
    
    return DF
def importGeo(filename):
    '''
    Imports a geographic dataset
    Inputs: filename (str)
    Outputs: DF (Pandas DF)
    '''
    geoDF = gp.read_file(filename)
    
    return geoDF

Create Plotting Function

def generatePlots(geoDF, state, yearRange):
    '''
    Generate a 2x3 plot that compares the unemployment rate with the 
    results of the presidential election of the same year.
    Inputs: geoDF, state (str), yearRange (list of strings)
    Outputs: None
    '''
    ## generate the plot
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2,3, constrained_layout = True, figsize = (13, 10))

    ## populate the plots
    for row in range(2):
        for col in range(3):
            
            ## set the current axis
            ax = axs[row, col]
        
            ## create the temporary dataframe based on the year and 
            ## state of interest
            temp = unempGeo[(unempGeo['year'] == yearRange[col]) & 
                            (unempGeo['Stabr'] == state)]
    
            ## if the row is 0, then plot unemployment data
            if row == 0:
                
                ## plot the map in the appropriate position
                rowPlot = temp.plot(column = 'Unemp_Rate', ax = ax, 
                                    edgecolor = '#999999', linewidth = .15, 
                                    vmin = .01, vmax = .15, cmap = 'YlOrBr', 
                                    legend=False)
                
                ## set the individual plot title
                ax.set_title(yearRange[col] + ' Unemployment Rate', loc = 'left')
            
            ## if the row is 1, then plot presidential data            
            if row == 1:
                ## plot the map in the appropriate position
                rowPlot = temp.plot(column = 'vote_percent', ax = ax, 
                                    edgecolor = '#999999', linewidth = .15, 
                                    vmin = .1, vmax = .9, cmap = 'RdBu', 
                                    legend=False)
                
                
                ## set the individual plot title
                ax.set_title(yearRange[col] + ' Presidential Election', 
                             loc = 'left')
    
            ## remove the axis (unnecessary for this sort of graphic)
            ax.set_axis_off()    
            
        ## add the colorbar scale (unemployment)          
        if row == 0:
            norm = mpl.colors.Normalize(vmin = 0, vmax = 1)
            ca = fig.colorbar(mpl.cm.ScalarMappable(norm=norm, cmap='YlOrBr'),
                         ax = axs[row, 2], shrink = .4, label = 'Unemployment Rate')
            
            ## manually set the colorbar-unemployment rate ratio
            ca.ax.set_yticklabels(["{:.0%}".format(i*.15) for i in ca.get_ticks()])

        ## add the colorbar scale (election results)   
        if row == 1:
            norm = mpl.colors.Normalize(vmin = .1, vmax = .9)
            cb = fig.colorbar(mpl.cm.ScalarMappable(norm=norm, cmap='RdBu'), 
                         ax = axs[row, 2], shrink = .4, label = 'Democratic Candidate Vote')
            
            cb.ax.set_yticklabels(["{:.0%}".format(i) for i in cb.get_ticks()])
    
    ## set the title message
    titleMessage = 'Timewise Comparison--The Unemployment Effect on Presidential Election Outcomes (County-Level)'
      
    ## add the title  
    plt.suptitle(titleMessage, x = 0, y = .995, horizontalalignment='left', fontsize = 16,
    fontweight = 'semibold')
    
    return plt

unempDF.columns = ['FIPS', 'Stabr', 'area_name', '2008', '2012', '2016']

## melt the dataframe
unempDF = pd.melt(unempDF, id_vars = ['FIPS', 'Stabr', 'area_name'], var_name = 'year',
                  value_name = 'Unemp_Rate')
                  
## convert unemployment rate to a percent
unempDF['Unemp_Rate'] = unempDF['Unemp_Rate'] /100

Import, Clean, & Reformat Election Data

## load the voter data
voteDF = importData('data/countypres_2000-2016.csv')
##    year    state state_po   county    FIPS  ...       candidate       party  \

## 2  2000  Alabama       AL  Autauga  1001.0  ...     Ralph Nader       green   
## 3  2000  Alabama       AL  Autauga  1001.0  ...           Other         NaN   
## 4  2000  Alabama       AL  Baldwin  1003.0  ...         Al Gore    democrat   
## 
##   candidatevotes  totalvotes   version  
## 0         4942.0       17208  20191203  
## 1        11993.0       17208  20191203  
## 2          160.0       17208  20191203  
## 3          113.0       17208  20191203  
## 4        13997.0       56480  20191203  
## 
## [5 rows x 11 columns]
## drop nas that hinder FIPS conversion and padding
voteDF = voteDF.dropna(subset=['FIPS'])

## convert FIPS to the appropriate type
voteDF['FIPS'] = voteDF['FIPS'].apply(lambda i: str(int(i)).zfill(5))

## convert year to string object for appropriate merging
voteDF['year'] = voteDF.astype(str)

## generate the vote percentage feature
voteDF['vote_percent'] = voteDF['candidatevotes'] / voteDF['totalvotes']

## filter the dataset to only the columns and years of interest
voteDF = voteDF[['year', 'FIPS', 'party', 'vote_percent']]

voteDF = voteDF[(voteDF['year'].isin(['2008', '2012', '2016'])) & 
                (voteDF['party'] == 'democrat')]
